      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Dec 2025 08:29:59 -0500</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://Ai3xGP.github.io/posts/powerstatus/</guid>
      
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Today, in Scripts to Work Less, I wanted to explore the idea of creating a small script to determine a machine’s startup, shutdown, and wake-up times.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the case of Windows, I know this information can already be obtained using tools like Plaso and others. However, I don’t want to spend 30 minutes just to answer a very specific question. So, let’s get our hands dirty. The first step is to identify which system events are related to these activities.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Notepad Plus Plus</title>
      <link>https://Ai3xGP.github.io/posts/notepad-plus-plus/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 08:07:43 -0500</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://Ai3xGP.github.io/posts/notepad-plus-plus/</guid>
      
      <description>&lt;p&gt;This investigation started after an alert generated by an EDR: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;Possible Masquerading Behavior&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Possible Masquerading Behavior indicates that a process, file, or connection is impersonating another entity:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Imitates a name&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Imitates a path&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Imitates behavior&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Attempts to hide its true identity&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The detected process was:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;C:\ProgramData\USOShared\svchost.exe -nostdlib -run C:\ProgramData\USOShared\conf.c&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This process was launched by the following parent process:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;C:\Users\User\AppData\Roaming\Bluetooth\BluetoothService.exe&amp;rdquo; -k&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let’s analyze these processes in detail.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At first glance, the execution of &lt;code&gt;svchost.exe&lt;/code&gt; from this location strongly indicates malware. We will analyze what this command does, but first we analyze the &lt;code&gt;USOShared&lt;/code&gt; directory:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
